{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658581"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:51:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:51:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20774"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20774"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96812"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13649"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79427"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11582"},{"type":"tags","id":"12427"},{"type":"tags","id":"12626"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32852"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96812"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man undergoes carotid endarterectomy. The surgical specimen shows areas of lipid accumulation, inflammation, and white deposits that feel gritty when cut with a scalpel.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiological process responsible for the gritty deposits in this atherosclerotic plaque?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium pyrophosphate crystal formation","Haemosiderin deposition from microhaemorrhages","Metastatic calcification from hypercalcaemia","Cholesterol crystallisation within the plaque","Dystrophic calcification in damaged tissue"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gritty white deposits in the atherosclerotic plaque represent \u003Cstrong\u003Edystrophic calcification in damaged tissue\u003C/strong\u003E. This process involves calcium salt deposition in areas of tissue damage or necrosis despite normal serum calcium levels. Advanced atherosclerotic plaques commonly develop dystrophic calcification, which appears macroscopically as white granular deposits that feel gritty when cut.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium pyrophosphate crystal formation\u003C/strong\u003E - These crystals are characteristic of pseudogout and typically affect articular cartilage, not vascular tissue. They have a different morphology and pathophysiology than dystrophic calcification.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemosiderin deposition from microhaemorrhages\u003C/strong\u003E - Haemosiderin is a golden-brown pigment derived from haemoglobin breakdown following haemorrhage. It does not produce white, gritty deposits.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetastatic calcification from hypercalcaemia\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs when calcium deposits in normal tissues due to elevated serum calcium levels. In contrast, dystrophic calcification occurs with normal calcium levels in damaged tissues.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholesterol crystallisation within the plaque\u003C/strong\u003E - While cholesterol crystals can form within atherosclerotic plaques, they appear microscopically as cleft-like spaces rather than gritty white deposits on gross examination.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDystrophic calcification in atherosclerotic plaques can contribute to vessel rigidity, reduced compliance, and altered plaque stability. This pathological process represents the body\u0027s response to chronic tissue damage within the vessel wall.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dystrophic calcification occurs in areas of tissue damage or necrosis despite normal serum calcium levels.","Atherosclerotic plaques are common sites for dystrophic calcification, appearing as gritty white deposits.","Dystrophic calcification can contribute to vessel rigidity and reduced compliance in atherosclerotic disease."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 2; page 65-66."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79427"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20774"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79427"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T22:37:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T22:40:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13649"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96812"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11582"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Cell injury, cell death and adaptations","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":1,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:12:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:12:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12427","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/